# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: milvus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Milvus is a high-performance, highly scalable vector database that runs efficiently across a wide range of environments, from a laptop to large-scale distributed systems.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] It is available as both open-source software and a cloud service.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Milvus is an open-source project under LF AI & Data Foundation distributed under the Apache 2.0 license.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Most contributors are experts from the high-performance computing (HPC) community, specializing in building large-scale systems and optimizing hardware-aware code.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Core contributors include professionals from Zilliz, ARM, NVIDIA, AMD, Intel, Meta, IBM, Salesforce, Alibaba, and Microsoft.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Unstructured data, such as text, images, and audio, varies in format and carries rich underlying semantics, making it challenging to analyze.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] To manage this complexity, embeddings are used to convert unstructured data into numerical vectors that capture its essential characteristics.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] These vectors are then stored in a vector database, enabling fast and scalable searches and analytics.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Milvus offers robust data modeling capabilities, enabling you to organize your unstructured or multi-modal data into structured collections.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] It supports a wide range of data types for different attribute modeling, including common numerical and character types, various vector types, arrays, sets, and JSON, saving you from the effort of maintaining multiple database systems.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Milvus was designed from day one to be a highly efficient vector database system.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] In most cases, Milvus outperforms other vector databases by 2-5x (see the VectorDBBench results).
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] In 2022, Milvus supported billion-scale vectors, and in 2023, it scaled up to tens of billions with consistent stability, powering large-scale scenarios for over 300 major enterprises, including Salesforce, PayPal, Shopee, Airbnb, eBay, NVIDIA, IBM, AT&T, LINE, ROBLOX, Inflection, etc.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] Milvus itself is fully stateless so it can be easily scaled with the help of Kubernetes or public clouds.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] In addition, Milvus components are well decoupled, with the three most critical tasks—search, data insertion, and indexing/compaction—designed as easily parallelized processes, with complex logic separated out.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] This ensures that the corresponding query node, data node, and index node can scale both up and out independently, optimizing performance and cost efficiency.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] In addition to the key search features mentioned above, Milvus also provides a set of features implemented around ANN searches so that you can fully utilize its capabilities.
[src:milvus/about-overview-md] In addition to primitive data types, Milvus supports various advanced data types and their respective applicable distance metrics.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] 🐦 Milvus is a high-performance vector database built for scale.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] It powers AI applications by efficiently organizing and searching vast amounts of unstructured data, such as text, images, and multi-modal information.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] 🧑‍💻 Written in Go and C++, Milvus implements hardware acceleration for CPU/GPU to achieve best-in-class vector search performance.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Thanks to its fully-distributed and K8s-native architecture, Milvus can scale horizontally, handle tens of thousands of search queries on billions of vectors, and keep data fresh with real-time streaming updates.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus also supports Standalone mode for single machine deployment.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus Lite is a lightweight version good for quickstart in python with `pip install`.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus is available as a fully managed service on Zilliz Cloud, with Serverless, Dedicated and BYOC options available.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] For questions about how to use Milvus, join the community on Discord to get help.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] For reporting problems, file bugs and feature requests in GitHub Issues or ask in Discussions.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] The Milvus open-source project is under LF AI & Data Foundation, distributed with Apache 2.0 License, with Zilliz as its major contributor.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] This installs `pymilvus`, the Python SDK for Milvus.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus is designed to handle vector search at scale.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] It stores vectors, which are learned representations of unstructured data, together with other scalar data types such as integers, strings, and JSON objects.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Users can conduct efficient vector search with metadata filtering or hybrid search.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus is trusted by AI developers to build applications such as text and image search, Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG), and recommendation systems.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus powers many mission-critical businesses for startups and enterprises.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] You can explore a comprehensive Tutorials Overview covering topics such as Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG), Semantic Search, Hybrid Search, Question Answering, Recommendation Systems, and various quick-start guides.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] These resources are designed to help you get started quickly and efficiently.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus integrates with a comprehensive suite of AI development tools, such as LangChain, LlamaIndex, OpenAI and HuggingFace, making it an ideal vector store for GenAI applications such as Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG).
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus works with both open-source embedding models and embedding services, in text, image and video modalities.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Milvus also provides a convenient utility `pymilvus[model]`, users can use the simple wrapper code to transform unstructured data into vector embeddings and leverage reranking models for optimized search results.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] The Milvus ecosystem also includes Attu for GUI-based administration, Birdwatcher for system debugging, Prometheus/Grafana for monitoring, Milvus CDC for data synchronization, VTS for data migration and data connectors for Spark, Kafka, Fivetran, and Airbyte to build search pipelines.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Check out https://milvus.io/docs/integrations_overview.md for more details.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] For guidance on installation, usage, deployment, and administration, check out Milvus Docs.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] For technical milestones and enhancement proposals, check out issues on GitHub.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] The Milvus open-source project accepts contributions from everyone.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] See Guidelines for Contributing for details on submitting patches and the development workflow.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] See our community repository to learn about project governance and access more community resources.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] For full instructions, see developer's documentation.
[src:milvus/blob-readme-md] Join the Milvus community on Discord to share your suggestions, advice, and questions with our engineering team.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus is an open-source project under the LF AI & Data Foundation and is distributed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus has been developed by Zilliz since 2017.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus joined Linux Foundation as an incubation project in January 2020 and became a graduate in June 2021.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] The details about its architecture and possible applications were presented at ACM SIGMOD Conference in 2021.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus 2.0, a major redesign of the whole product with a new architecture, was released in January 2022.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus 3.0 release candidate, which introduces elements of data lake / data warehouse based data processing, was published in May 2026.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus' similarity search engine relies on modified forks of third-party open-source similarity search libraries, such as Faiss, DiskANN (including the AiSAQ technology from KIOXIA) and hnswlib.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus includes optimizations for I/O data layout, specific to graph search indices.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus can be deployed as an embedded database, standalone server, or distributed cluster.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Zilliz Cloud offers a fully managed version.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus provides GPU accelerated index building and search using Nvidia CUDA technology via the Nvidia cuVS library, including the GPU-based graph indexing algorithm CAGRA.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus provides official SDK clients for Java, NodeJS, Python and Go.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] An additional C# SDK client was contributed by Microsoft.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] The database can integrate with DataDog, Prometheus and Grafana for monitoring and alerts, as well as generative AI frameworks Haystack, LangChain, IBM Watsonx, and those provided by OpenAI.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Several storage providers have built integrations with Milvus to support AI workloads and large-scale vector search.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Milvus is included in the SUSE AI platform product.
[src:milvus/milvus-vector-database] Red Hat OpenShift AI self-managed product supports deploying Milvus.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Formally, the nearest neighbor (NN) search problem is defined as follows: given a set S of points in a space M and a query point $q\in M$ , find the closest point in S to q.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Donald Knuth in volume 3 of *The Art of Computer Programming* (1973) called it the **post-office problem**, referring to an application of assigning to a residence the nearest post office.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] A direct generalization of this problem is a k-NN search, where we need to find the k closest points.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Most commonly M is a metric space and dissimilarity is expressed as a distance metric, which is symmetric and satisfies the triangle inequality.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Even more common, M is taken to be the d-dimensional vector space where dissimilarity is measured using the Euclidean distance, Manhattan distance or other distance metric.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] However, the dissimilarity function can be arbitrary.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] One example is asymmetric Bregman divergence, for which the triangle inequality does not hold.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Various solutions to the NNS problem have been proposed.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The quality and usefulness of the algorithms are determined by the time complexity of queries as well as the space complexity of any search data structures that must be maintained.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The informal observation usually referred to as the curse of dimensionality states that there is no general-purpose exact solution for NNS in high-dimensional Euclidean space using polynomial preprocessing and polylogarithmic search time.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The simplest solution to the NNS problem is to compute the distance from the query point to every other point in the database, keeping track of the "best so far".
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] This algorithm, sometimes referred to as the naive approach, has a running time of *O*(*dN*), where *N* is the cardinality of *S* and *d* is the dimensionality of *S*.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] There are no search data structures to maintain, so the linear search has no space complexity beyond the storage of the database.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Naive search can, on average, outperform space partitioning approaches on higher dimensional spaces.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The absolute distance is not required for distance comparison, only the relative distance.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In geometric coordinate systems the distance calculation can be sped up considerably by omitting the square root calculation from the distance calculation between two coordinates.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance comparison will still yield identical results.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Since the 1970s, the branch and bound methodology has been applied to the problem.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of Euclidean space, this approach encompasses spatial index or spatial access methods.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Several space-partitioning methods have been developed for solving the NNS problem.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Perhaps the simplest is the k-d tree, which iteratively bisects the search space into two regions containing half of the points of the parent region.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Queries are performed via traversal of the tree from the root to a leaf by evaluating the query point at each split.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Depending on the distance specified in the query, neighboring branches that might contain hits may also need to be evaluated.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] R-trees can yield nearest neighbors not only for Euclidean distance, but can also be used with other distances.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In the case of general metric space, the branch-and-bound approach is known as the metric tree approach.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Particular examples include vp-tree and BK-tree methods.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Using a set of points taken from a 3-dimensional space and put into a BSP tree, and given a query point taken from the same space, a possible solution to the problem of finding the nearest point-cloud point to the query point is given in the following description of an algorithm.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] (Strictly speaking, no such point may exist, because it may not be unique.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] This may not be the case, but it is a good heuristic.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] After having recursively gone through all the trouble of solving the problem for the guessed half-space, now compare the distance returned by this result with the shortest distance from the query point to the partitioning plane.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] This latter distance is that between the query point and the closest possible point that could exist in the half-space not searched.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] If this distance is greater than that returned in the earlier result, then clearly there is no need to search the other half-space.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] If there is such a need, then you must go through the trouble of solving the problem for the other half space, and then compare its result to the former result, and then return the proper result.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] An approximate nearest neighbor search algorithm is allowed to return points whose distance from the query is at most c times the distance from the query to its nearest points.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The appeal of this approach is that, in many cases, an approximate nearest neighbor is almost as good as the exact one.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In particular, if the distance measure accurately captures the notion of user quality, then small differences in the distance should not matter.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Proximity graph methods (such as navigable small world graphs and HNSW) are considered the current state-of-the-art for the approximate nearest neighbors search.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The methods are based on greedy traversing in proximity neighborhood graphs $G(V,E)$ in which every point $x_{i}\in S$ is uniquely associated with vertex $v_{i}\in V$ .
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The search for the nearest neighbors to a query *q* in the set *S* takes the form of searching for the vertex in the graph $G(V,E)$ .
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The basic algorithm – greedy search – works as follows: search starts from an enter-point vertex $v_{i}\in V$ by computing the distances from the query q to each vertex of its neighborhood $\{v_{j}:(v_{i},v_{j})\in E\}$ , and then finds a vertex with the minimal distance value.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] If the distance value between the query and the selected vertex is smaller than the one between the query and the current element, then the algorithm moves to the selected vertex, and it becomes new enter-point.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The algorithm stops when it reaches a local minimum: a vertex whose neighborhood does not contain a vertex that is closer to the query than the vertex itself.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] These works were preceded by a pioneering paper by Toussaint, in which he introduced the concept of a *relative neighborhood* graph.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Locality sensitive hashing (LSH) is a technique for grouping points in space into 'buckets' based on some distance metric operating on the points.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Points that are close to each other under the chosen metric are mapped to the same bucket with high probability.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The cover tree has a theoretical bound that is based on the dataset's doubling constant.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The bound on search time is *O*(*c*12 log *n*) where *c* is the expansion constant of the dataset.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In the special case where the data is a dense 3D map of geometric points, the projection geometry of the sensing technique can be used to dramatically simplify the search problem.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] This approach requires that the 3D data is organized by a projection to a two-dimensional grid and assumes that the data is spatially smooth across neighboring grid cells with the exception of object boundaries.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] These assumptions are valid when dealing with 3D sensor data in applications such as surveying, robotics and stereo vision but may not hold for unorganized data in general.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In practice this technique has an average search time of *O*(*1*) or *O*(*K*) for the *k*-nearest neighbor problem when applied to real world stereo vision data.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In high-dimensional spaces, tree indexing structures become useless because an increasing percentage of the nodes need to be examined anyway.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] To speed up linear search, a compressed version of the feature vectors stored in RAM is used to prefilter the datasets in a first run.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The final candidates are determined in a second stage using the uncompressed data from the disk for distance calculation.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The VA-file approach is a special case of a compression based search, where each feature component is compressed uniformly and independently.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The optimal compression technique in multidimensional spaces is Vector Quantization (VQ), implemented through clustering.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The database is clustered and the most "promising" clusters are retrieved.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Huge gains over VA-File, tree-based indexes and sequential scan have been observed.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Also note the parallels between clustering and LSH.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] There are numerous variants of the NNS problem and the two most well-known are the *k*-nearest neighbor search and the ε-approximate nearest neighbor search.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In some applications it may be acceptable to retrieve a "good guess" of the nearest neighbor.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] In those cases, we can use an algorithm which doesn't guarantee to return the actual nearest neighbor in every case, in return for improved speed or memory savings.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Often such an algorithm will find the nearest neighbor in a majority of cases, but this depends strongly on the dataset being queried.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Algorithms that support the approximate nearest neighbor search include locality-sensitive hashing, best bin first and balanced box-decomposition tree based search.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Nearest neighbor distance ratio does not apply the threshold on the direct distance from the original point to the challenger neighbor but on a ratio of it depending on the distance to the previous neighbor.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] It is used in CBIR to retrieve pictures through a "query by example" using the similarity between local features.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] More generally it is involved in several matching problems.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Fixed-radius near neighbors is the problem where one wants to efficiently find all points given in Euclidean space within a given fixed distance from a specified point.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] The distance is assumed to be fixed, but the query point is arbitrary.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] For some applications (e.g. entropy estimation), we may have *N* data-points and wish to know which is the nearest neighbor *for every one of those N points*.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] This could, of course, be achieved by running a nearest-neighbor search once for every point, but an improved strategy would be an algorithm that exploits the information redundancy between these *N* queries to produce a more efficient search.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] As a simple example: when we find the distance from point *X* to point *Y*, that also tells us the distance from point *Y* to point *X*, so the same calculation can be reused in two different queries.
[src:milvus/nearest-neighbor-search] Given a fixed dimension, a semi-definite positive norm (thereby including every Lp norm), and *n* points in this space, the nearest neighbour of every point can be found in *O*(*n* log *n*) time and the *m* nearest neighbours of every point can be found in *O*(*mn* log *n*) time.
[src:milvus/vector-database] A **vector database**, **vector store** or **vector search engine** is a database that stores and retrieves embeddings of data in vector space.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Vector databases typically implement approximate nearest neighbor algorithms so users can search for records semantically similar to a given input, unlike traditional databases which primarily look up records by exact match.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Use-cases for vector databases include similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation (RAG).
[src:milvus/vector-database] Vector embeddings are mathematical representations of data in a high-dimensional space.
[src:milvus/vector-database] In this space, each dimension corresponds to a feature of the data, with the number of dimensions ranging from a few hundred to tens of thousands, depending on the complexity of the data being represented.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Each data item is represented by one vector in this space.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Words, phrases, or entire documents, as well as images, audio, and other types of data, can all be vectorized.
[src:milvus/vector-database] These feature vectors may be computed from the raw data using machine learning methods such as feature extraction algorithms, word embeddings or deep learning networks.
[src:milvus/vector-database] The goal is that semantically similar data items receive feature vectors close to each other.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Vector retrieval can be combined with metadata filtering or lexical search to support filtered and hybrid retrieval workflows.
[src:milvus/vector-database] These techniques may also be combined in vector search systems.
[src:milvus/vector-database] In recent benchmarks, HNSW-based implementations have been among the best performers.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Conferences such as the International Conference on Similarity Search and Applications (SISAP) and the Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems (NeurIPS) have hosted competitions on vector search in large databases.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Vector databases are used in a wide range of machine learning applications including similarity search, semantic search, multi-modal search, recommendations engines, object detection, and retrieval-augmented generation.
[src:milvus/vector-database] An especially common use-case for vector databases is in retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), a method to improve domain-specific responses of large language models.
[src:milvus/vector-database] The retrieval component of a RAG can be any search system, but is most often implemented as a vector database.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Text documents describing the domain of interest are collected, and for each document or document section, a feature vector (known as an "embedding") is computed, typically using a deep learning network, and stored in a vector database along with a link to the document.
[src:milvus/vector-database] Given a user prompt, the feature vector of the prompt is computed, and the database is queried to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:milvus/vector-database] These are then automatically added into the context window of the large language model, and the large language model proceeds to create a response to the prompt given this context.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The density matching property of vector quantization is powerful, especially for identifying the density of large and high-dimensional data.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Since data points are represented by the index of their closest centroid, commonly occurring data have low error, and rare data high error.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] This is why VQ is suitable for lossy data compression.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] It can also be used for lossy data correction and density estimation.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Vector quantization is based on the competitive learning paradigm, so it is closely related to the self-organizing map model and to sparse coding models used in deep learning algorithms such as autoencoder.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] It is desirable to use a cooling schedule to produce convergence: see Simulated annealing.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Another simple method is LBG, which is based on k-means.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The algorithm can be iteratively updated with "live" data, rather than by picking random points from a data set, but this will introduce some bias if the data are temporally correlated over many samples.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Vector quantization is used for lossy data compression, lossy data correction, pattern recognition, density estimation and clustering.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Lossy data correction, or prediction, is used to recover data missing from some dimensions.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] It is done by finding the nearest group with the data dimensions available, then predicting the result based on the values for the missing dimensions, assuming that they will have the same value as the group's centroid.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] For density estimation, the area/volume that is closer to a particular centroid than to any other is inversely proportional to the density (due to the density matching property of the algorithm).
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Vector quantization, also called "block quantization" or "pattern matching quantization" is often used in lossy data compression.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] It works by encoding values from a multidimensional vector space into a finite set of values from a discrete subspace of lower dimension.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] A lower-space vector requires less storage space, so the data is compressed.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Due to the density matching property of vector quantization, the compressed data has errors that are inversely proportional to density.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The transformation is usually done by projection or by using a codebook.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] In some cases, a codebook can be also used to entropy code the discrete value in the same step, by generating a prefix coded variable-length encoded value as its output.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The set of discrete amplitude levels is quantized jointly rather than each sample being quantized separately.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] It is compressed by choosing the nearest matching vector from a set of *n*-dimensional vectors $[y_{1},y_{2},...,y_{n}]$ , with *n* < *k*.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] All possible combinations of the *n*-dimensional vector $[y_{1},y_{2},...,y_{n}]$ form the vector space to which all the quantized vectors belong.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Only the index of the codeword in the codebook is sent instead of the quantized values.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] This conserves space and achieves more compression.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Twin vector quantization (VQF) is part of the MPEG-4 standard dealing with time domain weighted interleaved vector quantization.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The usage of video codecs based on vector quantization has declined significantly in favor of those based on motion compensated prediction combined with transform coding, e.g. those defined in MPEG standards, as the low decoding complexity of vector quantization has become less relevant.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] VQ was also used in the eighties for speech and speaker recognition.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] Recently it has also been used for efficient nearest neighbor search and on-line signature recognition.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] In pattern recognition applications, one codebook is constructed for each class (each class being a user in biometric applications) using acoustic vectors of this user.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] In the testing phase the quantization distortion of a testing signal is worked out with the whole set of codebooks obtained in the training phase.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The codebook that provides the smallest vector quantization distortion indicates the identified user.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The main advantage of VQ in pattern recognition is its low computational burden when compared with other techniques such as dynamic time warping (DTW) and hidden Markov model (HMM).
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The main drawback when compared to DTW and HMM is that it does not take into account the temporal evolution of the signals (speech, signature, etc.) because all the vectors are mixed up.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] In order to overcome this problem a multi-section codebook approach has been proposed.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The multi-section approach consists of modelling the signal with several sections (for instance, one codebook for the initial part, another one for the center and a last codebook for the ending part).
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] As VQ is seeking for centroids as density points of nearby lying samples, it can be also directly used as a prototype-based clustering method: each centroid is then associated with one prototype.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] VQ has been used to quantize a feature representation layer in the discriminator of generative adversarial networks.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] The feature quantization (FQ) technique performs implicit feature matching.
[src:milvus/vector-quantization] It improves the GAN training, and yields an improved performance on a variety of popular GAN models: BigGAN for image generation, StyleGAN for face synthesis, and U-GAT-IT for unsupervised image-to-image translation.
